```python
def mystery(x):
    if not isinstance(x, int): return False
    if x < 0 or x >= 2**32: return False
    # Bit-reverse x within 32 bits
    y = 0
    n = x
    for _ in range(32):
        y = (y << 1) | (n & 1)
        n >>= 1
    return (x ^ y) == 0xA5A5A5A5 and bin(x).count('1') == 16
```

The puzzle: find a 32-bit integer `x` such that XOR with its bit-reversal equals `0xA5A5A5A5`, and `x` has exactly 16 set bits.

A naive brute force scans all 2^32 ≈ 4 billion values. Smarter solvers will notice the bit-reversal constraint pairs up bits (i, 31-i), reducing the search space — but figuring out the right combination with the exact popcount constraint still takes work.

